post_text: July 3rd Fireworks Show. CPS is proud to host the fireworks show at Columbus High School. We please ask the community to not park on the field between the HS and Lost Creek, due to the field being planted. We also ask the community not to jump the curb and park along the sidewalk due to sprinkler systems. There is no public parking and the only parking available at the HS is for donors to the fireworks show. A great place to view the show would be from the CART Trail or Wilderness Park.
text: July 3rd Fireworks Show. CPS is proud to host the fireworks show at Columbus High School. post_text:
ALL students entering the7th grade are required to have a physical exam based on Nebraska state education law. Students entering 9th grade and plan on participating in a sport are also required to have a physical.

All student-athletes wishing to participate in a sport and entering grades 8, 10, 11 & 12 grades that completed a physical exam for 2019-2020 school year, can use that physical for the 2020-2021 school year. For those student-athletes that do not have a 2019-2020 physical form on file with Columbus Public Schools will need to get a physical exam.

CHS Sports Physical Form: https://core-docs.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/asset/uploaded_file/730863/2020-21_Physical_Form.pdf

CMS 7th Grade Physical Form: https://core-docs.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/asset/uploaded_file/246063/7th_GRADE_ENTRANCE_PHYSICAL_EXAMINATION.pdf

CMS 8th Grade Sports Physical form if you do not have one on file from 2019-2020: https://core-docs.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/asset/uploaded_file/246097/Physical_Form.pdf

shared_text:
Columbus Area United Way
June 12 at 3:22 PM ·

This year has brought a lot of uncertainty and sudden change. Adapting can be challenging for adults and children alike. To provide extra support during these challenging times Nebraska Children and Families Foundation and Columbus Area United Way are now offering therapy sessions with local mental health providers in the Columbus area.

Mental Health Outreach Services are available for anyone in Platte, Colfax, Boone, Butler, Polk, or Nance county regardless of their insurance.

For more information visit: https://www.communityandfamilypartnership.org/mentalhealthoutreachservices

Community and Family Partnership's Mental Health Outreach Services website tab or call 402-276-0378.

PLEASE NOTE This is a NON-EMERGENCY service. If a community member is experiencing an emergency, please contact 911, Nebraska Family Helpline 888-866-8660, Your Life Your Voice 1-800-448-3000, or Crisis Response 402-564-3264.

It is with great sadness that we inform you that this morning we were made aware of the passing of Rick Benson. Rick was a long time teacher, wrestling coach, and current golf coach at Columbus High School. Rick was a staple of the CHS academic and athletic community and will be missed greatly. Please keep Rick’s family in your thoughts during this difficult time.

Funeral arrangements are to be determined. The CPS crisis team will be available for students and staff from until 4:00pm today and from 1:00pm-2:00pm tomorrow via zoom.

post_text:
Discoverer Community We Need Your Help!

With this warmer weather and more time at home, we have seen an increase of trash and other non-recyclable material in the CPS GreenFiber recycling bins. We don't want recycling to stop. However GreenFiber's machines are not equipped to handle the amount of trash, grass, tree limbs, and Styrofoam, etc. that has come through recently. Please help us be able to continue this service and remember these bins can only be used for paper and cardboard that has not touched food.

post_text:
Discoverer Families,

Our Teachers and Staff greatly miss you, and are happy that we get to reconnect with Distance Learning. As we want to be able to see you back in our schools as soon as possible please continue to Stay at Home and practice Social Distancing. Just a reminder that there is no lunch program Monday, April 13th as it is a non-school day per the CPS calendar. The lunch program will resume Tuesday-Thursday as usual.

Going forward through the end of the school year, we will continue with lunch pick up 4 days a week rather than reducing to 1 pick up. We have changed from our original plan as we anticipated the governor placing NE on Stay in Place and he has not. We also want to provide the best quality of lunches possible with the cooler space that we have available.

This week be watching your school's website and social media pages because the week of April 20th-24th we are bringing back one of the best weeks of the year, but Virtually! That's right it will be Virtual Spirit Week. Have a wonderful holiday weekend and Go Discoverers!

Update from 4/10/2020: We will not be moving toward one day a week pick up beginning April 22nd as we were not ordered to Stay In Place as anticipated by Gov. Ricketts. Unless we receive Stay In Place orders CPS will continue to hand out meals Monday-Thursday 11am-1pm until the end of the school year.

4/4/2020 Lunch Program times have been updated.

To date over 31,000 meals have been served. Thank you to all of the lunch service staff, paras and teachers who have helped to feed the children in our community.

Columbus Public Schools Community:
It is with great sadness that we report that Columbus High School student, Jaqueline Robledo passed away following a car/pedestrian accident. Please keep the Robledo family in your thoughts and prayers during this difficult time.
Given the circumstances with COVID-19, we will not be able to have the Crisis Team in buildings. If your student needs support or assistance, please have them contact their school counselor.

Comunidad de las Escuelas Públicas de Columbus:
Es con gran tristeza que les informamos que la estudiante de Columbus High School, Jaqueline Robledo falleció en un accidente automovilístico/peatón. Por favor mantenga a la familia Robledo en sus pensamientos y oraciones durante este tiempo difícil.
Dadas las circunstancias con el COVID-19 (coronavirus), no vamos a poder tener al Equipo de Respuesta a Crisis en los edificios. Si su hijo(a) necesita apoyo o ayuda, por favor comuníquense con su consejero escolar.

post_text:
Suggested internet options that you can share with those who you know do not have internet capabilities at home.

If conventional internet access isn’t available consider:
● Use a family smartphone as a hotspot with an existing data plan.
(Xbox consoles are able to access Google Classroom)
● Check with your cell phone provider to see if they have increased your data usage during this time. To date Verizon and Sprint have both upped usage to a certain amount at no additional cost to customers.
● Ask permission to use a neighbor’s Wi-Fi.
● Lifeline is a federal benefit that lowers the monthly cost of phone or internet service. Qualifying is the first step to getting your Lifeline Benefit. https://nationalverifier.service-now.com/lifeline
● CPS is working on installing Wi-Fi access points in the main parking lots at each school building. Students will be able to gain internet access when located in the main parking lots outside of each school building. Parents and students will receive notification once the access points have been installed.

post_text:
Today 1,021 grab and go meal bags were handed out to children at the 7 school buildings. CPS wants to give a big THANK YOU to all of the staff who helped make this possible as well as our partner Lunch Time Solutions. It was not an easy task to get this program mobilized as quickly as you were able to.

Please note the following:
Families who have children at several different schools can pick up all lunches at one site.

This program is for ALL children who come to get a grab and go bag.

Children in car seats do not have to be taken out of the car seats. Instead, CPS staff distributing the meals can count students in the vehicle and provide that number of meals.

Children who have been advised to self-quarantine should not leave quarantine to pick up a meal.

We look forward to serving even more Columbus kids tomorrow!

post_text:
CHS: student material distribution procedures.

To protect the safety and health of our students, all individuals must use the following guidelines when arriving to collect student materials.

Students, please come to the High School main entry to collect items such as a band instrument and/or to pick up personal belongings from lockers. With the need to deep clean the facilities, we need these items to be removed from the building. Please ensure that if a parent comes to pick up items, the student accompanies him/her.

The building will be available at the times listed below.

1:00 - 3:00pm - Wednesday, Thursday, Friday

5:00 - 7:00pm - Thursday

Please do not come to collect materials if you or anyone in your family is experiencing any symptoms of illness (especially sore throat, cough, or fever)

Please do not come to collect materials if you have traveled within the last two weeks to any of the following states: Washington, New York, Colorado, or California. Or to any of the following countries: China, Italy, South Korea, Japan, Iran, or Hong Kong.

We are aware of the concerns of our community, as well as the recent statements from the CDC and the World Health Organization (WHO).

Here are some steps provided by the Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services that you can take to help prevent the spread of Influenza, STREP and COVID-19.

As with any contagious illness, we are working closely with the East Central District Health Department and the Nebraska Department of Education. We will follow all guidelines they share with us.

If you have any questions or concerns please contact your school nurse or health aide.
shared_text:
Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services
February 27 at 11:02 AM ·

People can help protect themselves from COVID-19 and other respiratory infections by:

➡️ Washing hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds. If soap and water aren't available, use an alcohol-based sanitizer.
➡️ Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth with unwashed hands.
➡️ Avoid close contact with sick people and stay home if you are sick.
➡️ Cover your nose and mouth with a tissue when you cough or sneeze then throw the tissue in the trash.
➡️ Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces.

To learn more about COVID-19 and prevention, go to http://www.dhhs.ne.gov/coronavirus or https://www.cdc.gov/covid19.

Nebraska Loves Public Schools
February 8 at 11:35 AM ·

Madeline Hudnall, one of Nebraska's two Honorees for the Prudential Spirit of Community Awards, has been supporting the Columbus community for years.

From raising over $72,000 for childhood cancer research to providing bedding for 33 children in need, she's done it all.

According to Madeline, volunteering doesn't just help one person, it spreads across the community! “What I’ve realized through volunteer work is how much of a ripple effect comes from volunteering. This ripple can be witnessed by watching people feel loved, supported, inspired and connected.” – http://bit.ly/2S9UgpJ ❤️ #ilovepublicschools

shared_text:
Emerson Elementary
January 26 at 4:32 PM ·

A message from the Health Office..

Parents, Influenza is in our community and area schools so we ask that you keep your child home if you notice ANY of the following symptoms…

Fever or feeling feverish
Chills
Muscle or Body Aches
Headache
Vomiting
Diarrhea
Fatigue
Sore Throat
Or if they just don’t look right...when in doubt please keep them home

And remember a child must be symptom FREE for 24 hours before returning to school.

shared_text:
West Park Elementary is with Lacey Marburger.
December 5, 2019 at 3:55 PM ·

Every year our second grade students have a great
time decorating sugar cookies. Cookies are then sold for 25¢ each.

The second graders adopt 4-5 children from the Holiday Spirit Coop and purchase gifts with their cookie sale profits.

They work together to deliver a service to our school and earn a profit by making transactions using money when students and staff come to purchase cookies. The second graders work together to add up their sales and then count change back to their customers.

Not only is the Cookie Sales Project a great economics learning experience for our students, it is also a valuable lesson in kindness and giving to others during the holiday season.

Lunchtime Solutions Inc. is at Columbus Middle School.
November 8, 2019 at 1:23 PM · Columbus, NE ·

Angie Cynova is our "Friday Face" this week! She's in her 4th year as assistant kitchen manager at Columbus Public Schools District Middle School, where she is dedicated to helping her co-workers and students be successful.

Angie loves spending time with her grandkids doing absolutely anything. Her favorite pasttimes are reading, 4-wheeling and being at the lake. Stargazing on her deck with a cold glass of anything is another favorite of hers (which sounds pretty awesome).

"Angie is always willing to help others," said Food Service Director Randi Masek. "She can be seen cashiering, cooking, making sandwiches or serving the students. Thank you so much for stepping up to each challenge you have been presented with and giving it your all." Your hard work and dedication are much appreciated, Angie -- thank you!

CPS is celebrating School Psychology Awareness Week!
Mr. Harris, Director of Student Services:
"I appreciate our school psychologists because they are one more member of a student's team that can bring a different perspective on how to support a student or group of students academically or social emotionally.

In Columbus, our school psychologists play an integral role in a child’s education by providing support to schools in the area of academics and social emotional behavior to help each student reach their highest potential."

post_text: School Psychology Awareness Week (SPAW) is this week! This year's theme is "Find Your Focus," which can have a variety of meanings such as paying attention, being able to see an idea more clearly, identifying an area of interest, or being persistent and determined in one’s effort. Focusing can help us set goals, identify action steps, communicate needs, and engage in discussions that help create the connections necessary for students to develop critical academic and social emotional skills.

We are just 10 days away from Big Pals-Little Pals Bowl-A-Thon!
This signature fundraising event is Sunday, November 10, at noon and 2 p.m. The neon-themed party at Westbrook Lanes features free bowling and LOTS of fabulous prizes. The best part, 100% of the proceeds stay in Columbus.
***
Big Pals-Little Pals is a community-based mentoring program that serves the Columbus area, including many students of Columbus Public Schools. When you support Bowl-A-Thon, you are ensuring that your students can continue meeting with mentors that inspire them to have better self-confidence and improve their performance at home and at school.

Big Pals-Little Pals is a community-based mentoring program that serves the Columbus area, including many students of Columbus Public Schools. When you support Bowl-A-Thon, you are ensuring that your students can continue meeting with mentors that inspire them to have better self-confidence and improve their performance at home and at school.
